textDisplay:
If, out of all the books in the world, you choose to ruin one from Lovecraft, that just has to be a statement, especially with that Stephen King right next to it.



No offense, but Lovecraft's little finger made more contributions to the genre than Stephen King ever could. Especially considering that Lovecraft wrote because he felt like he had to, while nobody appreciated him, as opposed to King, whose entire writing career's peak was basically the result, the cause and a fuel, for his drug habits.

Pump any semi-literate moron full of cocaine, put them in front of a typewriter and tell them to think scary thoughts, and the result will be pretty much like Stephen King.
In order to make a Lovecraft, you need to basically take a very special, very intelligent little kid and stuff their head so full of existential terror, that they spend their entire life almost exploding from the pressure.


TlDr.: If you have aspirations of becoming a writer despite having almost zero talent, powerful stimulants like cocaine can do wonders for your career.
If all you have is talent, be prepared to be admired and adulated two or three decades after you die.
